<br>
Some nice well informed responses here.<br>
<br>
Personally I would recommend IDE  vrs SCSI. Why? Price. Pure and simple. And unless your running a big home business network that SCSI was intended for its not really needed.<br>
<br>
Hard Drives<br>
<br>
 They come in many flavors and such. 5400 7200 and 10,000 typically. With Drives being able to have ata 133 and support now.. and with a 7200+ spin drive you will have little or no problem. <br>
However, what you really want to look for is this. If you want a fast drive even at 7200 rpm spin. Have a look at the MS(millisecond) access time of the drive, typically faster access times will be more expensive, but since you were thinking of SCSI anyway its worth looking at.<br>
<br>
Processor's<br>
<br>
Well, what can we say here. Simply put its cost vrs performance. <br>
Athlon chips have better performance and are easier to overclock at the same MGHZ as Intel's chips. However they have one major inherant flaw. Heat. They just naturally run hot, easily fixed by a decent fan.<br>
<br>
Intel chips are rock solid in terms of performance and compatablility. For an Intel chip you get what you pay for. It may not be the fastest out there even with a matched Athlon chip bit its fairly bombproof and reliable. And the best part?.. Low heat usage.<br>
<br>
Heat kills computers plain and simple. Intel chips run with very low heat when compared to Athlon's of the same range.<br>
<br>
Interestingly enuff there was a test of both athlon and intel chips. Both 900's with no fan seeing how long each would run with NO FAN or cooling system attached.<br>
<br>
Intel got to a certain point and then shut the entire system down.. an inherant ablility imbeded into the chip(or so i'm told) the athlon you ask?.. well  it had no such safeguards and it eventually got so hot it made the motherboard catch fire.. heh.<br>
<br>
as for other perks?.<br>
<br>
Get a DDR (mother)board<br>
Get a GeForce 3 64mbDDR Vid Card<br>
Get a Soundblaster sound card<br>
<br>
Why to i recommend those? Well if one looks at the history of the gaming world it goes something like this.<br>
<br>
Sound.<br>
<br>
Game company's write code for the Soundblaster family first.. all else second.<br>
<br>
Video<br>
<br>
After the nasty little fall of the Voodoo family(which eq recommended originally btw) nVidia is now the leader for that area. With  most if not all code in games being writen for that family of video graphics cards first.<br>
<br>
So what kind of system would i recommend?<br>
<br>
Athlon (more bang for my buck) 1200-1800 range<br>
A really nice processor and case fan<br>
DDR Board<br>
DDR Ram(1 GB of ram btw on Win2k or XP as 98 cant use it)<br>
Soundblaster Live 5.1 in whatever flavor you like.<br>
Geforce 3 64mb DDR Vid Card<br>
60GB+ Hard Drive<br>
<br>
the other stuff CD-Rom etc. well its generic and stuff heh.<br>
<br>
as a side note. i'm currently in school and its nearly a 4-1 ratio in Athlons favor  in terms of processor. Simply because of the bang for your buch ratio.<br>
<br>
Sol<br>
<br>
P.S.<br>
Why are SCSI controllers listed in the IDE part of a listing? Simply put, the SCSI controller is a card very much like a network/sound/modem card in the sense that it fits into your normal PCI slot. And from that slot it comes with long cable very much like your normal IDE cable. here is where it differs.<br>
on your motherboard you have IDE1 and IDE2  . with these 2 controllers you are able to attatch a normal IDE cable with 2 ends on it. one in the middle and one on the end. With those 2 conrtollers you are able and therefore limited to 4 devices on your computer. EG 2 hard drives 1 dvd player and 1 CD rom.  watch your computer to boot up it will say<br>
Primary Master<br>
Seconday Master<br>
Primary Slave<br>
Seconday Slave.<br>
for a totall of 4 devices.<br>
<br>
what SCSI controller allows you to do is bypass that limitation of the motherboard and add more stuff, i think the maximum is 7 devices per controller card(and cable). and thats why its listed there. i hope this helps =)<br>
