<br>
The performance gained by SCSI, miniscule as it is, is also produced by the fact that better scsi cards do the I/O processing on a separate chip, effectively removing some of the main CPU's workload.<br>
<br>
RAID - a deeper view<br>
<br>
RAID stands for &quot;redundant array (of) inexpensive disks&quot;.  It is a FAULT TOLERANT method of using multiple small devices to create one large storage space. <br>
<br>
RAID comes in different flavors, noted by the number after the RAID.  RAID is avaible in 0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,10,53 and 0+1. The common use applications are RAID 0,1, and 5. Newer manufacturers of IDE &quot;raid&quot; cards do not specify that their solution is on the box, though they may on the manual.  Typically, IDE RAID is RAID 0.<br>
<br>
Descriptions of the different types of common RAID:<br>
<br>
RAID 0 is striped without fault tolerance, and as such, is not a true RAID.  I believe this lack of fault tolerance was mentioned earlier in this thread.  You have improved read/write performance, as the data is &quot;striped&quot; between two more more hard drives.  This utilizes both read/write heads simultaneously to access data that has been portioned across the multiple drives. The array appears as ONE logical storage device, which can then be partitioned as you see fit. If you lose one drive in the array, you lose all data.<br>
<br>
RAID 1 is duplexed/mirrored.  In a mirrored system, you have two drives attached to the same controller.  In a duplexed system, you have two drives attached to two different controllers. These drives read and write the same data at the same time.  If one drive fails, you configure the system to use the one remaining good drive while you work out swapping the other.  Duplexing is a design modification that builds in additional fault tolerance for the drive controller itself.<br>
<br>
RAID 5 (Most common RAID technology in PC and UNIX based server applications) Striped with Fault Tolerance.  You have improved read/write performance, as the data is &quot;striped&quot; between three or more hard drives.  This also utilizes both read/write heads simultaneously to access data that has been portioned across the multiple drives. The array , like RAID 0, also appears as ONE logical storage device, which can then be partitioned as you see fit. The difference is Fault Tolerance.  In addition to the data stripes that are written across the drives, a parity stripe is written as well...  RAID 5 arrays do not hold the same amount of data as a RAID 0 array, as a portion of EACH drive is used to store this parity stripe.  If any ONE drive dies in the array, the other drives and the parity software/hardware know how to recreate any requested information from the parity stripe.  replacing the dead drive and rebuilding the array brings it back to a fault tolerant state.<br>
<br>
